e. The Nordic countries are regarded as frontrunners in promoting equality, yet women's experiences on the ground are in many ways at odds with this rhetoric. Putting the spotlight on the lived experiences of women working in tech-driven research and innovation areas in the Nordic countries, this volume explores why, despite numerous programmes, women continue to constitute a minority in these sectors. Contributors flesh out the differences and similarities across different Nordic countries and explore how the shifts in labour market conditions have impacted on women in research and innovation. This is an invaluable contribution to global debates around the mechanisms that maintain gendered structures in research and innovation, from academia to biotechnology and IT.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aHigh technology industriesxSocial aspectszScandinavia. 0aResearchxSocial aspectszScandinavia. 0aSex discriminationzScandinavia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aCorneliussen, Hilde G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDralega, Carol Azungi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrange, Ida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, Gabriele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIkonen, Hanna-Mari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorvajärvi, Päivi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristensen, Guro Korsnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo